Visa Approval Facilitation

Problem Statement

Context

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

Note: This is a sample solution for the project. Projects will NOT be graded on the basis of how well the submission matches this sample solution. Projects will be graded on the basis of the rubric only.

# Convert Binary Columns to Numeric (0/1)

# Columns to convert
binary_cols = [
    'has_job_experience',
    'requires_job_training',
    'full_time_position',
    'case_status'
]

# Function to convert binary categorical columns to numeric (0/1)
def convert_binary_columns(df):
    binary_map = {
        'Y': 1,
        'N': 0,
        'Certified': 1,
        'Denied': 0
    }

    for col in binary_cols:
        df[col] = df[col].map(binary_map)

    return df

# Apply the conversion
data = convert_binary_columns(data)

# 1. Convert prevailing wage into annual wage
def convert_to_annual_wage(row):
    if row['unit_of_wage'] == 'Hour':
        return row['prevailing_wage'] * 2080   # 40 hrs/week  52 weeks
    elif row['unit_of_wage'] == 'Week':
        return row['prevailing_wage'] * 52
    elif row['unit_of_wage'] == 'Month':
        return row['prevailing_wage'] * 12
    else:  # 'Year'
        return row['prevailing_wage']

data['annual_wage'] = data.apply(convert_to_annual_wage, axis=1)

# 2. Create company age

data['company_age'] = 2016 - data['yr_of_estab']

# 3. Log-transform skewed features

data['annual_wage_log'] = np.log1p(data['annual_wage'])
data['employees_log'] = np.log1p(data['no_of_employees'])

Model Building

Model Evaluation Criterion

The goal of this project is to predict whether a visa application will be approved (1) or denied (0).

The model can make two kinds of incorrect predictions:

  1. False Positive (Type I Error)

    • Predicting Approved when the actual outcome is Denied.

  2. False Negative (Type II Error)

    • Predicting Denied when the actual outcome is Approved.

Which Error Is More Critical?

While both errors carry consequences, False Positives are more harmful because they directly impact:

  • Immigration compliance
  • Hiring timelines
  • Operational planning
  • Financial risk

Thus, the model must carefully avoid incorrectly approving cases that would be denied.

What Metric Should We Optimize?

The dataset shows a moderate class imbalance (~67% approved vs. ~33% denied), meaning accuracy alone is misleading so we should optimize F1-Score

Defining function to provide metric scores on the train and test set and a function to show confusion matrix.

In[35]:
def get_metrics(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test  = model.predict(X_test)
    y_pred_prob  = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

    metrics = {
        "Accuracy (Train)": accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train),
        "Accuracy (Test)": accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test),
        "Precision": precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test),
        "Recall": recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test),
        "F1-Score": f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test),
        "ROC-AUC": roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob)
    }
    return metrics
In[36]:
def plot_conf_matrix(model, X_test, y_test):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues')
    plt.xlabel("Predicted")
    plt.ylabel("Actual")
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
    plt.show()

In[38]:
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance
    """
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)

    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )
    return df_perf
In[39]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Model Comparison and Final Model Selection

In[60]:
def get_metrics_from_search(name, search_obj, X_test, y_test):
    """Extracts evaluation metrics from a fitted GridSearchCV/RandomizedSearchCV object."""
    best_model = search_obj.best_estimator_

    y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test)
    y_pred_prob = best_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

    return {
        "Model": name,
        "Accuracy": accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred),
        "Recall": recall_score(y_test, y_pred),
        "Precision": precision_score(y_test, y_pred),
        "F1-Score": f1_score(y_test, y_pred),
        "ROC-AUC": roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob)
    }


# Collect results
comparison_results = []

comparison_results.append(get_metrics_from_search("AdaBoost (Tuned)", ada_search, X_test, y_test))
comparison_results.append(get_metrics_from_search("Gradient Boosting (Tuned)", gb_search, X_test, y_test))
comparison_results.append(get_metrics_from_search("XGBoost (Tuned)", xgb_search, X_test, y_test))

# Create DataFrame
comparison_df = pd.DataFrame(comparison_results)
comparison_df = comparison_df.set_index("Model")

print("\n================ TUNED MODEL COMPARISON TABLE ================\n")
display(comparison_df.style.background_gradient(cmap="Blues"))

def evaluate_tuned_model(name, model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    print(f"\n================ {name} ================")

    # Only print best params if model came from RandomizedSearchCV
    if hasattr(model, "best_params_"):
        print("Best Parameters:", model.best_params_)
        estimator = model.best_estimator_
    else:
        print("Best Parameters: N/A (this is the final fitted model)")
        estimator = model

    # Predictions
    y_pred_train = estimator.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test  = estimator.predict(X_test)

    # Metrics
    print("\nTRAINING PERFORMANCE:")
    print("Accuracy :", accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
    print("Recall   :", recall_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
    print("Precision:", precision_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
    print("F1 Score :", f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train))

    print("\nTEST PERFORMANCE:")
    print("Accuracy :", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print("Recall   :", recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print("Precision:", precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print("F1 Score :", f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test))

    # Confusion matrix
    plot_conf_matrix(estimator, X_test, y_test)

# Extract the fitted preprocessor from the final model
prep = final_xgb.named_steps['preprocess']

# Get OHE categorical feature names
cat_encoder = prep.named_transformers_['cat']
cat_features = cat_encoder.get_feature_names_out()

# Get numeric feature names directly from transformer
num_features = prep.transformers_[1][2]

# Combine all final feature names in correct order
feature_names = list(cat_features) + list(num_features)

# Get feature importances from the XGBoost model
importances = final_xgb.named_steps['clf'].feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)

# Plot feature importances
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
plt.title("XGBoost Feature Importances", fontsize=16)

plt.barh(
    range(len(indices)),
    importances[indices],
    color='violet',
    align='center'
)

plt.yticks(
    range(len(indices)),
    [feature_names[i] for i in indices],
    fontsize=10
)

plt.xlabel("Relative Importance", fontsize=14)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The tuned XGBoost model highlights several variables that strongly influence visa case outcomes:

Top Predictive Factors

  • Higher education levels and relevant work experience correspond to higher approval likelihood.
  • Positions classified with hourly or yearly wage units show greater positive influence than weekly/monthly wage units.
  • Certain employment regions appear more favorable, suggesting geographic processing patterns.
  • Applicants from Europe and North America show slightly stronger approval correlations compared with other regions.

Actionable Insights

  • Education level is the strongest predictor of visa approval, with High School, Bachelors, Masters, and Doctorate categories ranking highest in feature importance.
  • Prior job experience significantly increases approval likelihood, suggesting adjudicators value demonstrated skill and work history.
  • Wage structure (hourly/yearly units) influences outcomes, indicating that clearer or more standardized pay formats may improve approval chances.
  • Geographic region of employment (West, Midwest, South, Northeast) affects predictions, implying regional differences in case processing or documentation practices.
  • Applicants continent of origin shows predictive influence, suggesting indirect associations with documentation norms or job categories.
  • Full-time vs. part-time status and job-training requirements also contribute, indicating that petition characteristics impact decision outcomes.
  • No single factor determines approvalthe model confirms decisions are shaped by a combination of education, experience, wage details, and regional attributes.

Recmmendations

  • Strengthen filings for applicants with lower education levels by including additional certifications, training records, or skills documentation.
  • Prioritize detailed documentation of work experience, including letters, project summaries, and quantitative achievements.
  • Standardize wage reporting using formats (hourly/yearly) that historically align with cleaner, more favorable approval patterns.
  • Implement regional training for HR teamsespecially in areas with historically lower approval signalsto ensure consistent and complete petition preparation.
  • Provide enhanced support for applicants from regions showing lower predicted approval, ensuring all required evidence is thorough and clearly presented.
